Rating: 3
Since everyone agrees that this recipe is a winner, I'm going to focus on what NOT to do. If you were raised on icky-sweet pecan pie (like I was) use this recipe AS IS, with NO changes. I thought I'd be smart and heed the advice of other reviewers who found the pie too sweet. However, removing the white and brown sugars is a mistake I won't repeat, making it too blah -- almost like it was "mass produced". Increasing the filling is also a mistake... it turns the filling into a custard with a texture that everyone found untraditional and disappointing. One more thing -- I used Grade A Amber, which is spectacular on waffles but is lost on this recipe. Next time I'll use Grade B, which is sweeter and smokier and will probably do this pie justice! I also recommend using syrup bought from the source (for example, Clark's Sugar House in Langdon NH ships it if you contact them at sugarhouse1@earthlink.net) but you can get it from any sugar house -- they're all pretty good. Yes, it's pricey, but I buy 3 gallons a year and it hasn't broken my bank account yet!!

